<subSubSection id="E2A8CDA1A6AD80C0DCF64D26DD0E95A5" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="type material">
<paragraph id="CB904453B50C6D8C9A140275DAA7000B" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Type material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="134875AD848AB4C602A8217F9D57B913" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="CBC73B3EC11C1CE2F0EC9B38167C0636" bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Holotype (male): BRAZIL: Minas Gerais</emphasis>
: Lassance, -17.83384, -44.50515, 568 m, Cachoeira da Palmeira, flotation of root mats and moss from side of waterfall and seepage, 2.iii.2018, leg. Benetti &amp; team; BR18-0302-04A (INPA). 
<emphasis id="02F33B5F6BF568DE90F18BA407EFADA6" bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
Paratypes (10): BRAZIL: 
<normalizedToken id="B55A55933221C9747D3AB181CCA8F601" originalValue="Pará">Para</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
: Rio Xingu Camp 
<geoCoordinate id="59452EA0BEDB131B6EDE9FD13E1E658D" degrees="52" direction="west" minutes="22" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-52.366665">52°22'W</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="B661047BD1881AB6ED013F1C1FB387C6" degrees="3" direction="south" minutes="39" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-3.65">3°39'S</geoCoordinate>
, Altamira, ca 60km S., 3.x.1986, leg. P. Spangler &amp; O. Flint, Colln. #6, 1st jungle stream on trail 1 (1, USNM); same, except 14.x.1986, Colln. #23, stream on left branch of trail 1 (3; SEMC, USNM); 
<emphasis id="6D251C601C16CBE3B6395571797CEE2C" bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Minas Gerais</emphasis>
: same data as holotype (2 INPA, 4 SEMC).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9BC05AF6E47F36E849A231363E9DCAE" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7AAFCAABE795BC87A24D2864EBBB34D5" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5C81EA81C877012935C024A07AB1DD02" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicName id="7383D314F41BCE660AFF100E4C3EB80D" authorityName="Girón &amp; Short" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crucisternum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crucisternum sinuatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuatus">
<emphasis id="43EA633F72AF17AE06C451CD8C5FE092" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Crucisternum sinuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E5CA64A4DECD1C6DAEDAA4A515F7C13A" genus="C." lsidName="C. escalera" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" rank="species" species="escalera">
<emphasis id="991D51D0B35120F9935E1735D6E12E73" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">C. escalera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6B894D7588DE814BAEF201921434F830" genus="C." lsidName="C. xingu" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" rank="species" species="xingu">
<emphasis id="5F5B071F2FB9AD9E032A8EFE9EF88188" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">C. xingu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shallowness of the punctation. In addition, it can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="9B6F080342DD0F8C40A9C9EB48A12D3A" genus="C." lsidName="C. xingu" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" rank="species" species="xingu">
<emphasis id="0385100499EC08DEAFA5BC1F7F4FC316" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">C. xingu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the aedeagus with median lobe constricted at midlength, continuing as a narrow and roundly pointed bar (see Fig. 
<figureCitation id="76F5AA6B26B380B2E000A91AEFEFD4E4" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Aedeagus of Crucisternum spp.: A-B Crucisternum ouboteri: A Guyana B Brownsberg C Crucisternum toboganensis D Crucisternum vanessae E-F Crucisternum xingu: E colln  6 F colln  23 G-H Cuscisternum sinuatus: G colln  23 H BR 18 - 0302 - 04 A I Crucisternum escalera J Crucisternum queneyi. Scale bars: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.768.24423.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/211216" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">6G, H</figureCitation>
; as opposed to gradually narrowing towards the apex, see Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D65998B9842A5717238C24589E521F2C" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Aedeagus of Crucisternum spp.: A-B Crucisternum ouboteri: A Guyana B Brownsberg C Crucisternum toboganensis D Crucisternum vanessae E-F Crucisternum xingu: E colln  6 F colln  23 G-H Cuscisternum sinuatus: G colln  23 H BR 18 - 0302 - 04 A I Crucisternum escalera J Crucisternum queneyi. Scale bars: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.768.24423.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/211216" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">6E, F</figureCitation>
), and the outer margins of the parameres, which are strongly constricted at apical third, continuing nearly parallel (as opposed to nearly straight to sinuate).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A9F70A0C22AE471078BEF6A0921EF53A" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="description">
<paragraph id="859D991D968F3DCD96A38A764F3FF6F2" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3AAD75A31923982E156D92E3C7D94F34" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
Body length 2.0-2.4 mm, width 1.1-1.4 mm. General coloration variable, either orange brown or uniformly dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C6C43D81A4B5C8CA65EA99343DA83E9F" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Habitus of Crucisternum spp.: A-D Crucisternum sinuatus: A dorsal view B lateral view C ventral view D head E-H Crucisternum xingu: E dorsal view F lateral view G ventral view H head. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.768.24423.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/211213" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">3A-D</figureCitation>
). Elytra with punctures shallowly marked. Aedeagus with outer margins of parameres strongly constricted at apical third, continuing nearly parallel towards apex; inner margins of parameres slightly concave only along apical sixth; median lobe constricted at midlength, continuing as a narrow and roundly pointed bar (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BB48C240A36E3CCFF034758E5F96287A" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Aedeagus of Crucisternum spp.: A-B Crucisternum ouboteri: A Guyana B Brownsberg C Crucisternum toboganensis D Crucisternum vanessae E-F Crucisternum xingu: E colln  6 F colln  23 G-H Cuscisternum sinuatus: G colln  23 H BR 18 - 0302 - 04 A I Crucisternum escalera J Crucisternum queneyi. Scale bars: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.768.24423.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/211216" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">6G, H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6E8F02AD3E43D5BAC3656CB73EAABB48" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="EB8C0FA5371D6ED9E870D0CA37AEC3C2" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8139AA479FC3EF12DA5F4DBA79329628" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
Named in reference to the abrupt constriction of the outer margins of the parameres at their apical third, with the Latin word 
<emphasis id="0738292EAD525874DE927DCE5FCDBF2D" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">sinuatus</emphasis>
meaning bent, curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6942996D5E2F2078F7CEFD7F7CBEDAEE" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="CF7E1F5DA6CCDD02F735F96ABD4C05B8" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5C852865FAFFB86BE6B1C31D38D5793" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">
Brazil (Minas Gerais, 
<normalizedToken id="5A71E605744F0ED27F9F6F21A67F0D30" originalValue="Pará">Para</normalizedToken>
). See Fig. 
<figureCitation id="187CAF293D8EC8E51E86D585B36D40C4" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution of Crucisternum species." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.768.24423.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/211218" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">7</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B9603F42B27189DBDF972EBAB1266AD1" pageId="7" pageNumber="120" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="E3B14BF7B52DC51F64E1C48D9076F6AD" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E2723FD312AC2983120309129E4C8E1E" pageId="7" pageNumber="120">The series from Lassance was collected by floating root mats and detritus that were on rock at the margin of a river and waterfall. The specimens from Altamira were collected in streams.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
